(78, 1, 'Dynapack Asia’s Apprentice Program', 'PT DYNAPACK INDONESIA', '<p>The leading and largest rigid plastic packaging company in Indonesia is looking for highly qualified professionals. We need people who are self motivated and team players, good in following skills of which are English both oral and written, communication and interpersonal, and computer skills, to join us in a competitive environment for the following position:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>APPRENTICE [Code : APST]</strong><br />\r\nDynapack Asia&rsquo;s Apprentice program is a special development program (one year) for young people. It is designed to give participants base-in-class hands on training, and it will give you an excellence head start for your carrier in this organization.<br />\r\nQualifications:<br />\r\n- Bachelor Degree (S1) or Academy (D3) in Engineering or Physics with min. GPA 3.00(Electrical/Mechanical/Metallurgical/ Industrial/Mechatronic/Accounting/Management)<br />\r\n- Fresh Graduate or max. 1 year working experience<br />\r\n- Fluent in English and good communication skill<br />\r\n- Good leadership skill<br />\r\n- Computer literate<br />\r\n- Willing to be located in all Dynaplast Plant (Tangerang/Bekasi/Cileungsi/Cikarang) and other company under the group (Bogor, Surabaya, Vietnam, Thailand, Malaysia and China)<br />\r\n- Expected entry date : October 2016</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Send application letter, curriculum vitae, recent photo 4x6, copy of identity card, copy of certificate and copy of transcript. Put the code on the left side of the envelope or put Email subject to:<br />\r\nCorporate HR<br />\r\n<strong>PT. Dynapack Indonesia<br />\r\nDynaplast Tower 9-10th Floor Jl. M.H. Thamrin No. 1<br />\r\nLippo Karawaci, Tangerang 15811<br />\r\nPhone : (62-21) 5463111, 5461112-15</strong><br />\r\nOr<br />\r\n<strong>eveline.hartono@dynapackasia.com</strong></p>\r\n', 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0, '2016-06-17', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2016-06-29 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 'Apprentice', 0),
(79, 1, 'Meteor Seeks Passionate People to Join', 'METEOR', '<p style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>METEOR</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><strong>We Are Hiring<br />\r\nMeteor seeks passionate people to grow with us</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>PHP Developer (code: PD2016)<br />\r\nCapabilities:</strong><br />\r\n- PHP development using several framework (Laravel , Code Igniter)<br />\r\n- Web UI Development using HTML5 , Java Script, CSS ,and using several framework (angular .js, bootstrap)<br />\r\n- Familiar with Mongodb , Mysql, and Redis<br />\r\n- Familiar with Web Services and RESTful</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Responsibilities:</strong><br />\r\n- Develop high performance and scalable backned engine<br />\r\n- Design and Develop clean and efficient RESTfull service<br />\r\n- Develop Web UI for BackEnd portals</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Nodejs Developer (code:ND2016)</strong><br />\r\n<strong>Capabilities:</strong><br />\r\n- NodejS and ExpressJS development&nbsp;<br />\r\n- Familiar with Mongodb , Mysql, and Redis<br />\r\n- Familiar with windows and Linux Platform<br />\r\n- Familiar with web service and RESTful</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Responsibilities</strong><br />\r\n- Development high performance and scalable backend &nbsp;egine<br />\r\n- Design and Develop efficient mobile API and Web UI for BackEnd portals<br />\r\n- Maintain code repository and code versions</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Mobile Developer (code: MD2016)</strong><br />\r\n<strong>Capabilities:</strong><br />\r\n- Mobile Development using HTML5 , and cross platform framework (Phonegap , Titanium, Lonic)<br />\r\n- Understanding Of &nbsp;Mobile platform compatibility and capability differences<br />\r\n- Familiar with Web Service and RESTful<br />\r\n<strong>Responsibilities:</strong><br />\r\n- Develop, enchance and maintain Mobile Applications (Android and IOS)<br />\r\n- Ensure Mobile Applications quality<br />\r\n- Maintain Code repository and code versions</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Bussines Analyst (Code: BA2016)<br />\r\nCapabilities:</strong><br />\r\n- Create business &amp; product presentations&nbsp;<br />\r\n- Strategic planning to indentify the organization&rsquo;s business needs<br />\r\n- Microsoft office (World, Excel, Powerpoint , visio)<br />\r\n<strong>Responsibilities</strong><br />\r\n- Create Business requirement, Functional requirement and non-functional requirements<br />\r\n- Bussiness analysis and business process engineering (Dataflow diagrams , Product flowchart )<br />\r\n- Managing product development process</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Status: Full time &ndash; Fresh graduates are welcomed<br />\r\nWork Area : BSD City, Tangerang<br />\r\n<strong>Benefits: Competitives salary plus achievement bonus<br />\r\nGeneral Qualificatiaon:</strong><br />\r\n- Fast learner , innovative , and good team player.&nbsp;<br />\r\n- Excellent ini analytical skill and problem solving able to work under pressure.<br />\r\n- Excellent communication skills able to crate good documentation</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Write role code as mail subject, shoot your resume &amp; portfolio to: Jobs@meteor.id</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>METEOR<br />\r\nWWW.METEOR.ID</strong></p>\r\n', 1, 1, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0, '2016-06-17', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2016-06-29 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 'Business Analyst, PHP Developer, Nodejs Developer, Mobile Developer', 0),
(80, 1, 'Freelance Desainer Grafis', 'PT. Yamazaki Indonesia', '<p>Kami ingin menginformasikan tentang lowongan freelance design grafis dengan spesifikasi sbb:<br />\r\n- Mahasiswa lulusan D3/S1<br />\r\n- Menguasai AI dan Photoshop<br />\r\n- Bersedia datang seminggu dua kali ke kantor<br />\r\n- Job scope: Facebook content digital imaging (mainly) dan design POP material<br />\r\n- Fee: sesuai dengan kedatangan/perhari</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Informasi tentang perusahaan kami:<br />\r\nPT. Yamazaki Indonesia<br />\r\nBread Manufacturer<br />\r\nwww.yzki.co.id<br />\r\nhttps://www.facebook.com/MYROTI.YAMAZAKI/<br />\r\nAlamat kantor:<br />\r\nSentral Senayan II lt.22,<br />\r\nJl. Asia Afrika No.8, Jakarta 10270<br />\r\nPIC: Tazkia Widyaputri (08111368608)</p>\r\n', 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, '2016-06-17', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2016-06-29 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 'Desainer Grafis (Freelance)', 0),
(81, 1, 'National UN Youth Volunteer', 'United Nations (UN)', '<p style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>PBB (UNITED NATIONS)</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>UN VOLUNTEER&nbsp;DESCRIPTION OF ASSIGNMENT</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Preamble:<br />\r\nThe United Nations Volunteers (UNV) programme is the UN organization that promotes volunteerism to support peace and development worldwide. Volunteerism can transform the pace and nature of development and it benefits both society at large and the individual volunteer. UNV contributes to peace and development by advocating for volunteerism globally, encouraging partners to integrate volunteerism into development programming, and mobilizing volunteers.<br />\r\nIn most cultures volunteerism is deeply embedded in long-established, ancient traditions of sharing and support within the communities. In this context, UN Volunteers take part in various forms of volunteerism and play a role in development and peace together with co-workers, host agencies and local communities.<br />\r\nIn all assignments, UN Volunteers promote volunteerism through their action and conduct. Engaging in volunteer activity can effectively and positively enrich their understanding of local and social realities, as well as create a bridge between themselves and the people in their host community. This will make the time they spend as UN Volunteers even more rewarding and productive.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>1. Type of Assignment: </strong>National UN Youth Volunteer<br />\r\nType of Assignment Place: Youth Volunteers assignments are always without family<br />\r\n<strong>2. Assignment Title:</strong> ICT Mainstreaming in Youth Development Assistant<br />\r\n<strong>3. Link with UNV Strategic Framework:</strong> Youth<br />\r\n<strong>4. Duty Station, Country</strong>: Jakarta, Indonesia<br />\r\n<strong>5. Duration (in months):</strong> 12 months<br />\r\n<strong>6. Expected Starting Date: August 2016</strong><br />\r\n<strong>7. Host Agency/Host Institute: P</strong>ulse Lab Jakarta (PLJ)<br />\r\n<strong>8. Organizational Context/Project:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In late 2012 Pulse Lab Jakarta was established through a partnership between the United Nations and the Ministry of National Development and Planning (Bappenas). The first innovation lab of its kind in Asia, Pulse Lab Jakarta brings together experts from United Nations agencies, the Indonesian government, non-governmental organisations and the private sectors to research and, most importantly, facilitate the adoption of new approaches for applying new, digital data sources and real-time analysis techniques to social development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pulse Lab Jakarta is a joint project of the United Nations through Global Pulse and the Government of Indonesia (GoI) through the Ministry of National Development Planning (Bappenas). Pulse Lab Jakarta is collaborating with the Government and UN country teams and partnering with leading private sector companies to explore how &ldquo;Big Data&rdquo; can support development and humanitarian actions in Indonesia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>9. Description of tasks:</strong><br />\r\nThe National UN Youth Volunteer will work under the overall guidance of Head of Pulse Lab Jakarta.<br />\r\nUnder the direct supervision of the Project Manager the National UN Youth Volunteer will undertake the following tasks:<br />\r\n- Assist the Project Manager and the Research Team:<br />\r\n- To plan and design projects, including creating a plan to communicate, advocate, campaign and outreach initiatives for ICT mainstreaming in facilitating youth participation to contribute to SDGs implementation;<br />\r\n- To respond to a variety of inquiries and information requests internally and externally related to ICT mainstreaming in facilitating youth participation to contribute to SDGs implementation;<br />\r\n- Assist the Pulse Lab Jakarta team with organising related activities to engage with UN agencies, relevant embassies and project partners;<br />\r\n- Assist the Pulse Lab Jakarta team to produce a task log of projects and research activities for drafting related reports;<br />\r\n- Contribute to building relationships with local organisations, groups or individuals, including universities, to engage people in youth participation activities;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Furthermore, UN Volunteers are required to:<br />\r\n- Strengthen their knowledge and understanding of the concept of volunteerism by reading relevant UNV and external publications and take active part in UNV activities (for instance in events that mark IVD);<br />\r\n- Be acquainted with and build on traditional and/or local forms of volunteerism in the host country;<br />\r\n- Reflect on the type and quality of voluntary action that they are undertaking, including participation in ongoing reflection activities;<br />\r\n- Contribute articles/write-ups on field experiences and submit them for UNV publications/websites, newsletters, press releases, etc.;<br />\r\n- Assist with the UNV Buddy Programme for newly-arrived UN Volunteers;<br />\r\n- Promote or advise local groups in the use of online volunteering, or encourage relevant local individuals and organizations to use the UNV Online Volunteering service whenever technically possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>10. Results/Expected Output:</strong><br />\r\n- Report produced on lessons learned and good practices on strategy through ICT mainstreaming in facilitating youth participation to contribute to SDGs implementation;<br />\r\n- Provided assistance related to researching and suggesting relevant ICT based tools (cheap, responsive, online mechanisms) to support Pulse Lab Jakarta&rsquo;s projects and research activities;<br />\r\n- Technological innovation applied to national youth engagement strategies;<br />\r\n- A learning session organised on use of technology for innovation and youth engagement for Pulse Lab Jakarta colleagues;<br />\r\n- Supported outreach to youth and marginalized citizens to engage in SDGs through ICT tools;<br />\r\n- A final statement of achievements towards volunteerism for development during the assignment, such as reporting on activities participated in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>11. Qualifications/Requirements:</strong><br />\r\n- Bachelor&rsquo;s degree in IT or CISCO NetAcademy Graduate equivalent preferred;<br />\r\n- Candidates with a good understanding of youth issues, technology and ICT in the Asia-Pacific region will be an added advantage;<br />\r\n- Demonstrated interest and/or experience in the field of youth, ICT, development, public/private partnerships;<br />\r\n- Good understanding and knowledge of ICT related topics/tools and interest in exploring their contribution to development issues;<br />\r\n- Effective written and verbal communication skills in Bahasa Indonesia and English;<br />\r\n- Good inter-personal and team building skills;<br />\r\n- Motivated to contribute towards peace and development and to serve others;<br />\r\n- Flexible and open to learning and new experiences.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>12. Living Conditions:</strong><br />\r\nThe position will be based in the Jakarta, capital of Indonesia, where basic living needs, including accommodation, banking facilities, medical facilities and telecommunications/internet services are readily available. All staple foods can be found in the markets, e.g.: rice, meat, vegetables, fruit, cooking oil, salt, etc. Many imported goods are available in Jakarta. Jakarta has numerous good restaurants with good health standards. The most used means of transportation are taxi or local bus. Mobile phone is the most reliable tool to communicate with colleagues and friends. Internet service is readily available at most apartment complexes. ATMs are everywhere in Indonesia and Western cards can usually be used to withdraw Indonesian Rupiah.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>13. Conditions of Service for national UN Youth Volunteers:</strong><br />\r\nA 12-month contract; with subsequent contract extensions subject to availability of funding, operational necessity and satisfactory performance. However, there is no expectation of renewal of the assignment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Travel to duty station (if applicable) and a Settling-In-Grant will be provided in the event duty station is not within commuting distance from the place of recruitment. A Volunteer Living Allowance (VLA) of Rp. 5.426.400 is provided monthly to cover housing, utilities and normal cost of living expenses. Life, health and permanent disability insurance are included, as well as final repatriation (if applicable) and resettlement allowance for satisfactory service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Description of Assignment prepared by the hosting project/UN Agency:<br />\r\nDerval Usher, Pulse Lab Jakarta Head of Office<br />\r\nDescription of Assignment approved by UNV Field Unit:<br />\r\nMs. Katherine Hodges, UNV Indonesia Programme Officer<br />\r\nDate of publishing: 29 April 2016</p>\r\n', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2016-06-28', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2016-08-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 'ICT Mainstreaming in Youth Development Assistant', 0),
(82, 1, 'Information and Communications Technology Mainstreaming in Youth Development Coordinator', 'United Nations (UN)', '<p style=\"text-align:center\">United Nations Volunteers is an equal opportunity programme which welcomes applications from qualified professionals. We&nbsp;are committed to achieving diversity in terms of gender, nationality and culture.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>UN VOLUNTEER DESCRIPTION OF ASSIGNMENT</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Preamble:<br />\r\n<strong>The United Nations Volunteers (UNV) programme</strong> is the UN organization that promotes volunteerism to support peace and development worldwide. Volunteerism can transform the pace and nature of development and it benefits both society at large and the individual volunteer. UNV contributes to peace and development by advocating for volunteerism globally, encouraging partners to integrate volunteerism into development programming, and mobilizing volunteers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">In most cultures volunteerism is deeply embedded in long-established, ancient traditions of sharing and support within the&nbsp;communities. In this context, UN Volunteers take part in various forms of volunteerism and play a role in development and peace together with co-workers, host agencies and local communities.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn all assignments, UN Volunteers promote volunteerism through their action and conduct. Engaging in volunteer activity can effectively and positively enrich their understanding of local and social realities, as well as create a bridge between themselves and the people in their host community. This will make the time they spend as UN Volunteers even more rewarding and productive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>1. Type of Assignment: N<strong>ational UN Youth Volunteer</strong><br />\r\nType of Assignment Place: Youth Volunteers assignments are always without family</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. Assignment Title: I<strong>nformation and Communications Technology Mainstreaming in Youth Development Coordinator</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. Link with UNV Strategic Framework: <strong>Youth</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>4. Duty Station, Country: Jakarta, Indonesia</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5. Duration (in months):&nbsp;<strong>12 months</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>6. Expected Starting Date: <strong>August 2016</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>7. Host Agency/Host Institute: <strong>UN Population Fund (UNFPA)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong>8. Organizational Context/Project:</strong><br />\r\n<strong>UNFPA</strong> is the lead UN agency for delivering a service aiming at a world where every pregnancy is wanted, every birth is safe, and every young person&#39;s potential is fulfilled. UNFPA expands the possibilities for women and young people to lead healthy and productive lives. Since UNFPA started working in 1969, the number &ndash; and rate &ndash; of women dying from complications of pregnancy or childbirth has been halved. Families are smaller and healthier. Young people are more connected and empowered than ever before.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>UNFPA </strong>has worked with the Government of Indonesia since 1972. The Ninth Country Programme (CP9) 2016&ndash;2020 provides a dynamic framework for UNFPA&rsquo;s engagement in Indonesia. Tapping into UNFPA&rsquo;s expertise and experiences, support is given to national partners in five priority output areas:<br />\r\n1. Improved policies and programmes to address barriers in ensuring rights-based maternal health and HIV-SRH linkages, including in humanitarian settings;<br />\r\n2. Strengthened rights-based, equitable and quality family planning policies and programmes, utilizing regional and international partnerships, including South-South Cooperation;<br />\r\n3. Improved policies and programmes to fulfil the rights and needs of adolescents and youth, including in humanitarian settings;<br />\r\n4. Improved policies and programmes to address barriers in the prevention and responses to gender-based violence and harmful practices, including in humanitarian settings; and<br />\r\n5. Increased availability of quality population data and robust analysis on population dynamics and its linkages with national policies and programmes related to sexual and reproductive health, gender equality, humanitarian response, and sustainable development.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nUNFPA will support the Government in fulfilling the rights and needs of youth and adolescents by developing an integrated and comprehensive National Action Plan on Youth Development and a Youth Development Index for Indonesia that capitalizes on the demographic dividend and improves the lives of young people in Indonesia. In improving the policy environment for greater investment in youth, one of UNFPA&rsquo;s key strategies is to promote youth leadership and participation through their networks to ensure active engagement in policy development and implementation, particularly on issues that directly affect their lives and future. UNFPA will support the Government to provide evidenced-based advocacy and policy to inform the development of a national youth strategy that capitalizes on the demographic dividend and improved outcomes for young people in Indonesia, through:<br />\r\n<strong>a. Advocacy and supporting Government </strong>to establish a national youth working group to inform Government&rsquo;s Youth Policy through knowledge sharing;<br />\r\n<strong>b. Supporting the development of a National Action Plan on Youth Development (2016 &ndash; 2019) and a Youth Development Index (YDI) for Indonesia</strong>, focusing on capitalizing on the demographic dividend. It is coordinated by the National Development Planning Agency - Bappenas (with multi-stakeholder partnerships), in collaboration with the Ministry of Youth and Sports (MOYS);<br />\r\n<strong>c. Strengthening the role of youth organizations and networks in Indonesia </strong>to enable meaningful youth participation in development and policy making with Government, including in humanitarian settings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">Furthermore, UNFPA has committed to achieve universal access to sexual and reproductive health (SRH), promote reproductive rights, reduce maternal mortality and improve the lives of adolescents and young people. Unala is a project on adolescent sexual and reproductive health services and led by private sector in Yogyakarta. Unala is using social franchise as its strategy to ensure the service quality and to reach the most needed young people. UNFPA has supported demand generation activities including youth get-togethers and engagement (with youth based organisations, NGOs, schools), internet promotion and social media engagement. It advocates for the rights of young people, including the right to accurate information and services related to sexuality and reproductive health. Empowered with knowledge and skills to protect themselves and make informed decisions, they can realize their full potential and contribute to economic and social transformation. Unala was launched in July 2014 in Yogyakarta and nine general practitioners in seven clinics have joined the social franchise. Currently the project is fully supported by UNFPA, but the long term plan is for Unala to become self-sustainable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>9.&nbsp;Description of tasks:</strong><br />\r\nUnder the overall guidance of the UNFPA Representative and under the direct supervision of the National Programme Officer (NPO) on Youth and Adolescent Sexual and Reproductive Health (ASRH), the National UN Youth Volunteer is expected to assist the NPO on Youth and ASRH to support the development of the Youth Development Index. The NPO on Youth and ASRH will facilitate collaboration and coordination activities with international and national counterparts, most especially Bappenas, the Ministry of Youth and Sports, other Government institutions, NGOs, youth networks and other UN agencies, as well as development partners.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The National UN Youth Volunteer will work within the Youth and ASRH team, with the support of the National UN Volunteer for Youth Engagement and the National UN Volunteer for ASRH.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Under the direct supervision of the NPO on Youth and ASRH the National UN Youth Volunteer will undertake the following tasks:<br />\r\n- Support the NPO on Youth and ASRH to create spaces and tools through ICT mainstreaming which will facilitate youth participation in contributing to SDGs implementation;<br />\r\n- Infuse innovation and technology for the development of national youth policies (Youth Development Index and a national youth strategy) through citizen engagement, crowdsourcing, online collaboration with youth and Government on the strategy development;<br />\r\n- Facilitate and identify ways of how connectivity of people, processes and data play an inclusive role for young people across Indonesia (including the minority youth and those hard to reach) through cheap, responsive, online mechanisms to increase youth participation, activism and innovative thinking for the development of the Youth Development Index;<br />\r\n- Work closely with UNFPA-Youth Advisory Panel (YAP) in Indonesia, participate in UNFPA Country Office activities and workshops, and facilitate knowledge sharing particularly those are related with youth issues, feeding into the UNDP/UNV Regional Youth Project ;<br />\r\n- Support UNFPA to maintain the Unala website, including monitor requests and queries or traffic from the Unala website. Unala is a project funded by UNFPA on provision of ASRH information and services for young people through private sector;<br />\r\n- The National UN Youth Volunteer will be expected to work closely with the Regional Youth Peer Coordinator (located in Bangkok Regional Office), participate in regional team activities and workshops, and facilitate knowledge sharing between project countries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Furthermore, UN Volunteers are required to:<br />\r\n- Strengthen their knowledge and understanding of the concept of volunteerism by reading relevant UNV and external publications and take active part in UNV activities (for instance in events that mark IVD);<br />\r\n- Be acquainted with and build on traditional and/or local forms of volunteerism in the host country;<br />\r\n- Reflect on the type and quality of voluntary action that they are undertaking, including participation in ongoing reflection activities;<br />\r\n- Contribute articles/write-ups on field experiences and submit them for UNV publications/websites, newsletters, press releases, etc.;<br />\r\n- Assist with the UNV Buddy Programme for newly-arrived UN Volunteers;<br />\r\n- Promote or advise local groups in the use of online volunteering, or encourage relevant local individuals and organizations to use the UNV Online Volunteering service whenever technically possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>10. Results/Expected Output:</strong><br />\r\n- Report produced on lessons learned and good practices on strategy through ICT mainstreaming in facilitating youth participation to contribute to SDGs implementation;<br />\r\n- ICT based tools (cheap, responsive, online mechanisms) are researched and suggested for use, to connect people, improve processes and data access for young people across Indonesia (including the minority youth and those hard to reach) feeding into the UNDP/UNV Regional Youth Project;<br />\r\n- Report on Unala social media achievements and analytics;<br />\r\n- Technological innovation applied to national youth engagement strategies;<br />\r\n- A learning session organised on use of technology for innovation and youth engagement for UNFPA colleagues;<br />\r\n- Supported outreach to youth and marginalized citizens to engage in SDGs through ICT tools;<br />\r\n- A final statement of achievements towards volunteerism for development during the assignment, such as reporting on activities participated in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>11. Qualifications/Requirements:</strong><br />\r\n- Bachelor&rsquo;s degree in IT or CISCO NetAcademy Graduate equivalent preferred;<br />\r\n- Candidates with a good understanding of youth issues, technology and ICT in the Asia-Pacific region will be an added advantage;<br />\r\n- Demonstrated interest and/or experience in the field of youth, ICT, development, public/private partnerships;<br />\r\n- Good understanding and knowledge of ICT related topics/tools and interest in exploring their contribution to development issues;<br />\r\n- Effective written and verbal communication skills in Bahasa Indonesia and English;<br />\r\n- Good inter-personal and team building skills;<br />\r\n- Motivated to contribute towards peace and development and to serve others;<br />\r\n- Flexible and open to learning and new experiences.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>12. Living Conditions:</strong><br />\r\nThe position will be based in the Jakarta, capital of Indonesia, where basic living needs, including accommodation, banking facilities, medical facilities and telecommunications/internet services are readily available.&nbsp;All staple foods can be found in the markets, e.g.: rice, meat, vegetables, fruit, cooking oil, salt, etc. Many imported goods are available in Jakarta. Jakarta has numerous good restaurants with good health standards. The most used means of transportation are taxi or local bus.&nbsp;Mobile phone is the most reliable tool to communicate with colleagues and friends. Internet service is readily available at most apartment complexes. ATMs are everywhere in Indonesia and Western cards can usually be used to withdraw Indonesian Rupiah.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>13. Conditions of Service for national UN Youth Volunteers:</strong><br />\r\nA 12-month contract; with subsequent contract extensions subject to availability of funding, operational necessity and satisfactory performance. However, there is no expectation of renewal of the assignment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Travel to duty station (if applicable) and a Settling-In-Grant will be provided in the event duty station is not within commuting distance from the place of recruitment. A Volunteer Living Allowance (VLA) of Rp. 5.426.400 is provided monthly to cover housing, utilities and normal cost of living expenses. Life, health and permanent disability insurance are included, as well as final repatriation (if applicable) and resettlement allowance for satisfactory service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Description of Assignment prepared by the hosting project/UN Agency:<br />\r\nDr. Annette Robertson, UNFPA Indonesia Representative</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Date: 26 April 2016<br />\r\nDescription of Assignment approved by UNV Field Unit:<br />\r\nMs. Katherine Hodges, UNV Indonesia Programme Officer<br />\r\nDate: 26 April 2016</p>\r\n', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2016-06-28', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2016-08-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 'The United Nations Volunteers (UNV) programme', 0);
