(83, 1, 'Technology, Youth and Innovation Coordinator', 'United Nations (UN)', '<p style=\"text-align:center\">United Nations Volunteers is an equal opportunity programme which welcomes applications from qualified professionals. We are comitted to achieving diversity in terms of gender, nationality and culture.</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>UN VOLUNTEER&nbsp;DESCRIPTION OF ASSIGNMENT</strong></span><br />\r\n<br />\r\nPreamble:<br />\r\nThe United Nations Volunteers (UNV) programme is the UN organization that promotes volunteerism to support peace and development worldwide. Volunteerism can transform the pace and nature of development and it benefits both society at large and the individual volunteer. UNV contributes to peace and development by advocating for volunteerism globally, encouraging partners to integrate volunteerism into development programming, and mobilizing volunteers.<br />\r\nIn most cultures volunteerism is deeply embedded in long-established, ancient traditions of sharing and support within the communities. In this context, UN Volunteers take part in various forms of volunteerism and play a role in development and peace together with co-workers, host agencies and local communities.<br />\r\nIn all assignments, UN Volunteers promote volunteerism through their action and conduct. Engaging in volunteer activity can effectively and positively enrich their understanding of local and social realities, as well as create a bridge between themselves and the people in their host community. This will make the time they spend as UN Volunteers even more rewarding and productive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>1. Type of Assignment:&nbsp;National UN Youth Volunteer</strong><br />\r\nType of Assignment Place: Youth Volunteers assignments are always without family<br />\r\n<br />\r\n2. Assignment Title: T<strong>echnology, Youth and Innovation Coordinator</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\n3. Link with UNV Strategic Framework: <strong>Youth</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\n4. Duty Station, Country: <strong>Jakarta, Indonesia</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\n5.&nbsp;Duration (in months): <strong>12 months</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\n6.&nbsp;Expected Starting Date: <strong>August 2016</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\n7. Host Agency/Host Institute:&nbsp;<strong>UNICEF</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>8. Organizational Context/Project:</strong><br />\r\nIn Asia and the Pacific, the Regional Youth Project (RYP) aims to empower and support young people to more effectively engage with the SDGs. Using SDG-16 as an entry point the RYP will focus on peacebuilding along with building youth capacities for political participation in decision making. UNDP and UNV will channel support through three approaches: (i) facilitating knowledge-sharing and networking, (ii) harnessing youth volunteering for change; and (iii) catalyzing youth innovation for social entrepreneurship and sustainable development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This initiative will be a learning and development opportunity created to empower youth. It will also open up prospects for young&nbsp;women and men to be familiarized with the UN&rsquo;s work, give them a holistic experience of the organization and understanding of the development issues as well as find ways to contribute their ICT skills in support of initiatives contributing to sustainable development.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>UNICEF Innovation Lab Jakarta Indonesia:</strong><br />\r\nThe strategic priorities of the 2016-2020 UNICEF Indonesia Country Program Document include the need for evidence-based advocacy to ensure the rights of the most vulnerable children are addressed in policy formulation, while identifying and emphasizing the importance of child and youth participation in the process of generating such evidence and knowledge.&nbsp;Key partners beyond government will include faith-based, adolescent, youth and other civil society organizations, academia, research institutions, the media, influential individuals as well as the private sector, both at national and sub-national level. Existing networks and alliances will be convened to coalesce into a coalition for children in Indonesia to support the implementation of the National Agenda for Children and enhance the realization of children&rsquo;s rights. Among the groups specifically addressed are adolescents and young people. The innovation function within the programme will further expand its adolescent and youth-oriented communication platforms such as U-Report to create space for their participation in the country&rsquo;s development processes. It will also invest in facilitating the implementation of new and innovative solutions to programmatic challenges.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nGiven Indonesia&rsquo;s huge youth population, with approximately 81.3 million children under 18 and nearly half of the population being youth, tapping into the huge potential of young people and partnering with them on the issue of social development and children&rsquo;s rights, youth and adolescents are an important group for UNICEF. One of the key innovations initiatives identified by the Country Office is establishing a youth engagement platform via the use of social media, similar in concept to U-Report &ndash; a regular interaction with the community via SMS and social media broadcasting which was rolled out successfully and developed by UNICEF in Uganda.<br />\r\nIn order to successfully maintain and develop U-Report in Indonesia, there needs to be a consistent, systematic, and cohesive functioning platform and programme. This programme and platform must be dedicated to continually engaging youth and adolescents, coordinate with diverse partners including those in the technology &amp; innovation eco-system. In&nbsp;order to deliver a platform that interacts with youth in Indonesia. U-Report here in Indonesia and the additional youth oriented innovation initiatives of the Innovation Lab hinges on effectively engaging and empowering young people to participate as active citizens, develop solutions to local problems and engage in affirmative social action. To further this aim, UNICEF Indonesia needs dedicated national expertise to facilitate the functioning of the U-Report Indonesia programme, manage its growing community and maintain meaningful engagement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>9. Description of tasks:</strong><br />\r\nThe Innovation Lab sits within the Communications Cluster of UNICEF Indonesia. The Innovation Lab team consists of an Innovation Lab Lead, and two National UN Volunteers for Youth Engagement who report to the Innovation Lab Lead. The Innovation Lab Lead reports to the Chief of Communications. The National UN Youth Volunteer will work alongside the two National UN Volunteers and also report to the Innovation Lab Lead.<br />\r\nUnder the direct supervision of the Innovation Lab Lead the National UN Youth Volunteer will undertake the following tasks:<br />\r\n&bull; Assist the Innovation Lab Lead with a youth programming review and technology analysis of U-Report Indonesia and make recommendations on new features, programmatic development, and maintaining the programme&rsquo;s relevance to Indonesian youth;<br />\r\n&bull; Work together with the Innovation Lab youth engagement team to coordinate and plan a small scale pilot of an innovation hack-a-thon for children&rsquo;s rights, with a look at producing simple testable app prototypes to address a children&rsquo;s rights challenge. This methodology will test using UNICEF&rsquo;s Innovation Lab&rsquo;s Social Innovation Bootcamp and/or UPSHIFT framework in Indonesia;<br />\r\n&bull; Map the innovation and technology eco-system focusing on technology companies creating platforms for youth to participate in governance. This work will be done with current Innovation Lab youth engagement officers who will support in prioritizing the mapping work to identify the best potential companies to target for strategic partnership with UNICEF innovations;<br />\r\n&bull; Support the Innovation Team to develop the Innovation Lab&rsquo;s network and connections with the UX, innovation, design, and tech start up communities in Indonesia through an engagement mechanism;<br />\r\n&bull; Support the Innovation Lab in assessing the Innovation Lab&rsquo;s digital safety profile from a youth perspective &amp; participatory research;<br />\r\n&bull; Bring ideas to infuse new thinking on facilitating cross-country knowledge-sharing and networking of the youth-based knowledge creation and capture;<br />\r\n&bull; Together with National CISCO Youth Volunteers and UNV/UNDP Regional Youth Project Team, identification of ways at how connectivity of people, processes and data play an inclusive role for the most excluded and stigmatized young people;<br />\r\n&bull; Assist in identifying opportunities and solutions stemming from the UNV/UNDP Regional Youth Project of direct interest to young people where ICT and innovation as well the skills young women and men possess could have the biggest impact from a youth and inclusion perspective level;<br />\r\n&bull; The National UN Youth Volunteer will be expected to work closely with the Regional Youth Peer Coordinator (located in Bangkok Regional Office), participate in regional team activities and workshops, and facilitate knowledge sharing between project countries;<br />\r\n&bull; Document and consolidate lessons learned, best practices, case studies, case stories, testimonials in written, picture and video form of the learning journey together with the other National Youth Volunteers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Furthermore, UN Volunteers are required to:<br />\r\n&bull; Strengthen their knowledge and understanding of the concept of volunteerism by reading relevant UNV and external publications and take active part in UNV activities (for instance in events that mark IVD);<br />\r\n&bull; Be acquainted with and build on traditional and/or local forms of volunteerism in the host country;<br />\r\n&bull; Reflect on the type and quality of voluntary action that they are undertaking, including participation in ongoing reflection activities;<br />\r\n&bull; Contribute articles/write-ups on field experiences and submit them for UNV publications/websites, newsletters, press releases, etc.;<br />\r\n&bull; Assist with the UNV Buddy Programme for newly-arrived UN Volunteers;<br />\r\n&bull; Promote or advise local groups in the use of online volunteering, or encourage relevant local individuals and organizations to use the UNV Online Volunteering service whenever technically possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>10. Results/Expected Output:</strong><br />\r\n&bull; A small scale pilot hack-a-thon for children&rsquo;s rights implemented, resulting in lessons learned and recommendations for running another hack-a-thon;<br />\r\n&bull; Analysis report with ideas for keeping U-Report Indonesia youth friendly, and current with youth trends in technology &amp; innovations in Indonesia;<br />\r\n&bull; Assisted with partnership and collaboration mapping report for key youth technology partners;<br />\r\n&bull; Digital safety review produced and youth friendly digital safety reccomendations identified;<br />\r\n&bull; New ways to use data and technology to include marginalised and stigmatised youth in development competitions suggested, prototyped, and initially tested;<br />\r\n&bull; Lessons learned and best practices are shared with other National Youth UN Volunteers in the regional project;<br />\r\n&bull; A final statement of achievements towards volunteerism for development during the assignment, such as reporting on the number of volunteers mobilized, activities participated in and capacities developed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>11. Qualifications/Requirements:</strong><br />\r\n&bull; Bachelor&rsquo;s degree in IT or CISCO NetAcademy Graduate equivalent preferred;<br />\r\n&bull; Demonstrated interest and/or experience in the field of youth, ICT, development, public/private partnerships;<br />\r\n&bull; Good understanding and knowledge of ICT related topics/tools and interest in exploring their contribution to development issues;<br />\r\n&bull; Strong written and spoken communication skills in both Bahasa Indonesia and English;<br />\r\n&bull; Good command of MS Office (especially Word, PowerPoint, Excel and Publisher);<br />\r\n&bull; Ability for analytical and strategic thinking;<br />\r\n&bull; Detail-oriented and excellent at multi-tasking;<br />\r\n&bull; A proactive and result oriented approach to work;<br />\r\n&bull; High degree of independence, creativity and ability to motivate;<br />\r\n&bull; Ability to work under pressure and against tight deadlines;<br />\r\n&bull; Excellent change management skills;<br />\r\n&bull; Be able to thrive in a multicultural, team environment;<br />\r\n&bull; Knowledge Sharing/Continuous Learning;<br />\r\n&bull; Candidates with a good understanding of youth issues, technology and ICT in the Asia-Pacific region will be an added advantage.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>12. Living Conditions:</strong><br />\r\nThe position will be based in the Jakarta, capital of Indonesia, where basic living needs, including accommodation, banking facilities, medical facilities and telecommunications/internet services are readily available. All staple foods can be found in the markets, e.g.: rice, meat, vegetables, fruit, cooking oil, salt, etc. Many imported goods are available in Jakarta. Jakarta has numerous good restaurants with good health standards. The most used means of transportation are taxi or local bus. Mobile phone is the most reliable tool to communicate with colleagues and friends. Internet service is readily available at most apartment complexes. ATMs are everywhere in Indonesia and Western cards can usually be used to withdraw Indonesian Rupiah.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>13. Conditions of Service for national UN Youth Volunteers:</strong><br />\r\nA 12-month contract; with subsequent contract extensions subject to availability of funding, operational necessity and satisfactory performance. However, there is no expectation of renewal of the assignment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Travel to duty station (if applicable) and a Settling-In-Grant will be provided in the event duty station is not within commuting distance from the place of recruitment. A Volunteer Living Allowance (VLA) of Rp. 5.426.400 is provided monthly to cover housing, utilities and normal cost of living expenses. Life, health and permanent disability insurance are included, as well as final repatriation (if applicable) and resettlement allowance for satisfactory service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Description of Assignment prepared by the hosting project/UN Agency:<br />\r\nJeffrey Hall, UNICEF Indonesia Innovations Lab Lead</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Date of publishing: 11 March 2016<br />\r\nDescription of Assignment approved by the hosting project/UN Agency:<br />\r\nMichael Klaus, UNICEF Indonesia Chief of Communications<br />\r\nDate: 11 March 2016<br />\r\nDescription of Assignment approved by UNV Field Unit:<br />\r\nKatherine Hodges, UNV Indonesia Programme Officer<br />\r\nDate: 11 March 2016</p>\r\n\r\n<p>United Nations Volunteers is an equal opportunity programme which welcomes applications from qualified professionals. We are committed to achieving diversity in terms of gender, nationality and culture.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sebagai catatan kami, apabila ada siswa/I bapak yang melamar, mohon untuk cc ke email agautama@cisco.com agar kami bisa memberikan referensi.</p>\r\n', 1, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0, 0, '2016-06-28', NULL, NULL, NULL, '2016-08-01 00:00:00', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 1, 'UN VOLUNTEER ', 0),
